If you color each individual sprinkle that you used to model, it will lock it to that one so that ALL small ones will be green, etc
  Also you can't change the color distribution(Hue Saturation R) of the colours easily, they will ALL be the same shades of those colours. no off white, green, etc
To give multiple objects the same material, first create the material on an object, then (with the object still selected) 'Shift + Click' on the other objects you wish to apply it to, THEN 'shift + click' the object with material again
  'Ctrl + L' (after selecting all objects as typed out above) -> 'Link Materials' -> 'Link Materials' = Link Menu (will allow you to link multiple options for the objects)
  After linking materials you will now see a '5' next to the name showing that it is now linked to 5 different materials
'Shift + A' (in shading tab) -> 'Input' -> 'Object Info' Node = Can do many things, the one we are using for the donuts is 'Random' - Will assign a random value between 0 and 1 for each individual sprinkle
  'Object Info' Random -> Base Color 'Principled BSDF'
'Shift + A' (in shading tab) -> 'Converter' -> 'Color Ramp' = Can change into any color - Sprinkles of different colors - Every sprinkle will have a different shade now - Linear Gradient
  'Object Info' Random -> FAC 'Color Ramp' Color -> Base Color 'Principled BSDF'
Tut - Do above 2 inputs in shading nodes, and now change 'Color Ramp' from 'Linear'(gradient) to 'Constant'(will be only the colors you choose - now slider will be the % of those with the color
Arrange the slider to set the amount of color for each 
'Principled BSDF' Metallic Shader = 0-1 slider = You can make the white/yellow sprinkles 'Metallic' to make them silver and gold 
Non Metallic = Dielectric Materials (scientific term) = Materials should either be 0(none) or 1(All) 
'Ctrl + Shift + D' = Duplicate, but retain the connection
Tut - Duplicate the 'Color Ramp' Remove all the non metallic colors, gold(yellow), White(silver) - 
  'Object Info' Random -> FAC 'Color Ramp' Color -> Metallic 'Principled BSDF' / Also need to reduce the 'Roughness' in 'Principled BSDF' for a more metallic look
If you reduce the roughness in the 'Principled BSDF' it will remove the roughness for all, to fix this, Duplicate the 'Color Ramp' of the ones you want to make shiny - 
  'Color Ramp' Color -> Roughness 'Principled BSDF' = Now with the changed 'Value' Slider, select which colours you want to have roughness(or not) - Basically the inverted values above 
For shiny = Metallic + No Roughness
Donut is finished after that, 

